(33, 'Conflate', 'en-gb', 'combine (two or more sets of information, texts, ideas, etc.) into one', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/xconflate_gb_1.mp3', 'k?n?fle?t', 'combine (two or more sets of information, texts, ideas, etc.) into one', '', 'late Middle English (in the sense ‘fuse or melt down metal’): from Latin conflat- ‘kindled, fused’, from the verb conflare, from con- ‘together’ + flare ‘to blow’', 'verb', '01/02'),
(34, 'Cynosure', 'en-gb', 'a person or thing that is the centre of attention or admiration', '', '?s??n????', 'person or thing that is centre of attention or admiration', '', 'late 16th century: from French, or from Latin cynosura, from Greek kunosoura ‘dog\'s tail’ (also ‘Ursa Minor’), from ku?n, kun- ‘dog’ + oura ‘tail’. The term originally denoted the constellation Ursa Minor, or the pole star which it contains, long used as a guide by navigators', 'noun', '02/02'),
(35, 'Dalliance', 'en-gb', 'a casual romantic or sexual relationship', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/dalliance_gb_1.mp3', '?dal??ns', 'casual romantic or sexual relationship', 'Berkeley was my last dalliance with the education system', 'Middle English (in the sense ‘conversation’): from dally+ -ance', 'noun', '03/02'),
(36, 'Demesne', 'en-gb', 'a piece of land attached to a manor and retained by the owner for their own use', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/demesne_gb_2.mp3', 'd??me?n', 'land attached to manor', 'a levy of one tenth on property in the royal demesne', 'Middle English: from Old French demeine (later Anglo-Norman French demesne) ‘belonging to a lord’, from Latin dominicus, from dominus ‘lord, master’. Compare with domain', 'noun', '04/02'),
(37, 'Demure', 'en-gb', 'reserved, modest, and shy (typically used of a woman)', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/demure_gb_1.mp3', 'd??mj??', 'reserved and shy', 'a demure knee-length skirt', 'late Middle English (in the sense ‘sober, serious, reserved’): perhaps from Old French demoure, past participle of demourer ‘remain’ (see demur); influenced by Old French mur ‘grave’, from Latin maturus ‘ripe or mature’. The sense ‘reserved, shy’ dates from the late 17th century', 'adjective', '05/02'),
