(45, 'Dulcet', 'en-gb', '(especially of sound) sweet and soothing (often used ironically)', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/dulcet_gb_1.mp3', '?d?ls?t', 'sweet and soothing', '', 'late Middle English doucet, from Old French doucet, diminutive of doux, from Latin dulcis ‘sweet’. The Latin form influenced the modern spelling', 'adjective', '13/02'),
