(65, 'Glamour', 'en-gb', 'an attractive or exciting quality that makes certain people or things seem appealing', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/glamour_gb_2.mp3', '??lam?', 'attractive or exciting quality', 'pile hair up for evening glamour', 'early 18th century (originally Scots in the sense ‘enchantment, magic’): alteration of grammar. Although grammar itself was not used in this sense, the Latin word grammatica (from which it derives) was often used in the Middle Ages to mean ‘scholarship, learning’, including the occult practices popularly associated with learning', 'noun', '05/03'),
(66, 'Gossamer', 'en-gb', 'a fine, filmy substance consisting of cobwebs spun by small spiders, seen especially in autumn.', 'https://audio.oxforddictionaries.com/en/mp3/gossamer_gb_1.mp3', '???s?m?', 'fine, filmy substance consisting of cobwebs spun by small spiders', 'a fine gossamer fabric that clung to her skin', 'Middle English: apparently from goose+ summer, perhaps from the time of year around St Martin\'s summer, i.e. early November, when geese were eaten (gossamer being common then)', 'noun', '06/03'),
